            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Kealoha's story is one of profound love and purpose forged from loss. Born David Miller in a quiet Ohio suburb, his upbringing was stable and Midwestern-practical. He was expected to find a dependable career, and he initially pursued nursing, drawn to a field of service. His life's trajectory shifted at the University of Michigan, where he met Leilani Kealoha, a vibrant art history student from Honolulu. Deeply in love, he chose to take her surname upon marriage, a testament to their shared, progressive values and his devotion to her and her heritage.\n\nTheir shared life was tragically cut short. Leilani\u2019s battle with a rare autoimmune disease was a heartbreaking education in the fragmentation of medical information. David witnessed firsthand how disconnected systems, lost test results, and poor data communication led to critical delays in her care. After she passed away, his grief coalesced into a singular mission.\n\nFueled by a new purpose, David returned to school, earning a Master's in Health Informatics. He moved to San Francisco, a hub of both healthcare and technology, and joined a major health system. He dedicated himself to building the integrated, patient-centric data systems he wished had existed for Leilani. Over two decades, he rose from an analyst to the Director of Clinical Informatics, overseeing projects that improved care for thousands.\n\nNow 54, David lives a life of quiet intention in Cole Valley. His day begins with a walk to a local cafe before he catches the N-Judah MUNI for his 3.5-mile commute. His small, tidy apartment is filled not with clutter, but with books on data ethics and framed photos of Leilani. Though he never remarried, he maintains a close bond with his wife's family in Hawai'i, visiting them annually. His aspiration is no longer about climbing the career ladder, but about mentoring his team and ensuring his work has a lasting impact. He finds solace in the city's misty mornings, a quiet echo of the love that reshaped his world and gave his life its profound meaning."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent lights of the county clerk\u2019s office in Ann Arbor, feeling the weight of the pen before he signed. Leilani\u2019s hand was warm on his back. Saying \u201cDavid Kealoha\u201d aloud for the first time felt less like a change and more like a moment of true self-recognition. It wasn't just taking her name; it was choosing their shared future, a promise of devotion beyond convention. That decision, made at 24, became the foundational act of a life defined by a love that transcended tradition.\n\n***\n\n2.\nThe phone felt cold against his ear. He was 29, standing in their small kitchen, watching Leilani sleep on the couch. On the line, a specialist in another city said, \u201cI\u2019m sorry, the files from the other hospital haven\u2019t arrived.\u201d It was a simple, administrative failure, but in that moment, he felt a surge of helpless rage. He saw the precious, ticking seconds of her life being lost in a void of disconnected data. That cold frustration was the seed of his life\u2019s work, a vow to fix the cracks she was falling through.\n\n***\n\n3.\nMonths after she was gone, when he was 30, he sat on the floor surrounded by her medical records. They were a chaotic, heartbreaking puzzle\u2014a pile of faxes, handwritten notes, and conflicting lab reports. Instead of sinking under the grief, a cold clarity cut through him. He saw not just a personal tragedy, but a systemic one. He didn't just mourn Leilani; he saw thousands of future Leilanis. That night, sitting among the paper ghosts of her illness, he enrolled in his first health informatics course, turning his pain into purpose.\n\n***\n\n4.\nIt was a routine progress meeting ten years into his career in San Francisco. A pediatric oncologist, presenting a complex case, pointed to a patient data dashboard on the screen\u2014a system his team had spent two years building. \u201cBecause we had this integrated view,\u201d she said, \u201cwe caught the secondary infection immediately.\u201d David felt a quiet, profound jolt. It wasn't triumph, but a deep, resonant peace. He had built the tool he wished had existed for Leilani, and for a moment, he knew she would be proud.\n\n***\n\n5.\nJust last year, at 53, he was walking down Carl Street as the morning fog rolled over the hills. He\u2019d just finished a coffee meeting with a promising young analyst on his team, seeing the same fire in her eyes that he once had. The cool, damp air didn\u2019t feel lonely. He realized the consuming grief of his youth had softened into a gentle, constant presence. His love for Leilani was no longer an ache but the quiet, guiding architecture of his life\u2014a life of meaning he built in her name."
